&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;ve written a spike using Antlr to reverse-engineer a grammar. I need
&gt; to parse legacy product config files with Java.
&gt;
&gt; I now need to decide how such a beast will be unit tested, and
&gt; I&#39;m wondering
&gt; if anyone else has designed unit tests for exercising Antlr-generated
&gt; parser classes.  I looked around the mail archives and the websites and
&gt; didn&#39;t find any mention of Antlr anywhere.
&gt;
&gt; I want to create a collection of ascii texts and ensure the parser reads
&gt; all of them properly.  The result from my spike parser is an actual
&gt; object, not a string, so I guess I need some way of creating an
&gt; &#39;expected result&#39; object, the input text, and comparing the parser&#39;s
&gt; returned object.
&gt;
&gt; Has anyone done this sort of parser testing before?  Do you have any
&gt; suggestions or pitfall warnings I should consider before I dig myself
&gt; in too deep?
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m guessing a single unit test might look something like this:
&gt;
&gt;   public void test1() {
&gt;     DebugConfig expected = new DebugConfig(1,2,3,4,5,6,7);
&gt;     String testInput = &quot;debugLevel { config 1&#92;n ...}&quot;;
&gt;     StringInputStream in = new StringInputStream( testInput );
&gt;     Parser foo = new com.aravox.parser.DebugConfigParser(in);
&gt;     assertEquals( expected.toString(), foo.toString());
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt; I don&#39;t know if I want to have a bunch of methods like this with
&gt; strings hard coded, or if I want to somehow store the test input
&gt; and some serialized form of the expected object in a single file.
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m also not sure if I should create a separate method for each
&gt; test string, or just make one big method out of it.  I&#39;m thinking
&gt; the former, so that one failure doesn&#39;t kill all remaining tests.
&gt;
&gt; I lean toward the above  &#39;cause I already know how to do it, even
&gt; if it does mean hardcoding the test inputs as strings in the test code.
&gt;
&gt; Any thoughts?
&gt;
